    "summary": "Pan-Africanism — the intellectual and political movement asserting the unity of African peoples and the African diaspora on the basis of shared cultural heritage and the common experience of colonialism and slavery — reached its political peak in the decades surrounding African independence. The movement had roots in the nineteenth century and was shaped by thinkers such as W.E.B. Du Bois and Marcus Garvey, whose pan-African congresses in the early twentieth century provided a platform for African and diaspora intellectuals.\n\nIn the post-World War II era, pan-Africanism became a practical political program associated particularly with Ghana's Kwame Nkrumah, who envisioned a federated United States of Africa. The [[event:3661|Organization of African Unity]] founded in 1963 was the institutional expression of pan-African solidarity, though it reflected the preference of most African leaders for cooperation among sovereign states rather than continental political union. Pan-Africanism also provided the ideological context for international opposition to colonialism, Rhodesia's white minority rule, and the [[event:2684|apartheid]] system. By century's end, the movement had evolved into Afrocentrism in cultural and academic spheres, and the African Union founded in 2001 attempted to revive integrationist ambitions with more institutional structure than its predecessor.",
